    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1918-01-07T06:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1918-01-07T06:00:00-05:00" n="32"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d32">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">File No. 861.00/916</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Ambassador in Japan</hi> (<persName corresp="#p_MRS1"
                        type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Morris</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#center">[Telegram]</seg>
                </opener>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Tokyo</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1918-01-07T20:00:00+09:00">
                            <hi rend="italic">January 7, 1918, 8 p.m.</hi>
                        </date>
                        <lb/> [<hi rend="italic">Received January 7, 4.50 p.m.</hi>]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>Upon my communicating with Vice Minister for Foreign Affairs, your telegram of
                    January 5, 3 p.m.,<note n="1" xml:id="d32fn1">See telegram to the Consul at
                        Vladivostok, <hi rend="italic">ante</hi>, <ref target="#pg_19">p.
                        19</ref>.</note> he advised me that 26th Lord <persName corresp="#p_CR1"
                        >Robert Cecil</persName> had urged upon Japanese Ambassador in London the
                    inadvisableness of antagonizing Maximalist Party now in control in Russia, but
                    that on the 1st instant he had urged the necessity of taking some steps short of
                    actual military intervention to protect military stores lying at Vladivostok.
                    Vice Minister for Foreign Affairs said his Government is waiting further
                    explanation of the apparent change of attitude of the British Government and of
                    its immediate intentions before taking final decision. In reply to inquiry as to
                    his personal feeling, he stated he thought it would be premature to land troops,
                    as he understood British Foreign Office proposes, inasmuch as that might incur
                    anti-Ally feeling.</p>
                <p>
                    <persName corresp="#p_SJF1">Stevens</persName> announces credit entirely
                    satisfactorily arranged.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <persName corresp="#p_MRS1">
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Morris</hi>
                        </persName>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
